==Description==
𝕿𝖍𝖊 𝖈𝖆𝖑𝖑...is a normal two-story house with a very small basement. The house appears to have recently been cleaned, and there is a strongly noticeable lavender odour filling the air. Everything is neat and organized, appearing to be a typical suburban home from the 2000s to around the early 2010s.

Outside, there is always night and rain. While one can never leave the house, windows may be opened. What can be seen is a small, poorly lit suburban street.
{{Blurimage|file=thesapa.png|caption=the house.|hovertext=my new home?.}}
Despite the eerie conditions, the house radiates a soft sense of comfort, warmth, and happiness for reasons never apparent. This feeling persists. But never really seems natural.

Approximately 10 minutes after entering the level, a landline phone will ring. The phone can be in different locations — usually in the living room, the kitchen, the basement, or in one of the second-floor bedrooms. On the floor beneath the phone, there always will be a tiny poem written on a piece of paper:

"If you answer, the past will fade away.
If you ignore it, no one will remember you."

Answering the call will make you forget one memory — but what memory you forget is purely random. Ignore the call. You simply will not be here anymore.

Picking up the phone, one of three possible things can be heard:

*Hushed, troubled breathing.
*Muffled laughter and sobbing way off in the distance.
*Someone you love weeping and Screaming your name.

The calls take anywhere from 1 to 4 minutes. After the line disconnects, something always gets stolen away — but you won't be able to understand what you lost until too late. You might not remember how to walk, how to speak, or how to recall anything.

That is all that will remain — a wanderlust to wander — seeking something nameless in some other place.

Until 10 minutes later.

